## 1. The "Warp-Drive" Architecture (Direct-to-RAM)
For "instant" teleportation, the .h5 file should not live on a disk; it should live in System RAM using the HDF5 core driver. This allows your Python backend to read and write at memory bus speeds (tens of gigabytes per second) rather than SSD speeds.

* In-Memory "Core" Driver: Open the file with driver='core' to keep the entire timeline in active memory for zero-latency "Time Travel".
* SWMR (Single-Writer Multi-Reader): Use [SWMR mode](https://docs.h5py.org/en/stable/swmr.html) to allow your mobile H5 page to read the latest state while the Python backend is still writing it, without any locking delays.

## 2. High-Speed Python Core (teleport_engine.py)
This script uses low-level HDF5 calls and the latest file format to bypass standard Python overhead.

import h5pyimport numpy as npimport time
# OPENING WITH 'CORE' DRIVER FOR MAXIMUM SPEED# backing_store=True saves a copy to disk on close, but works in RAM for nowf = h5py.File("teleport_vault.h5", "a", driver='core', backing_store=True, libver='latest')
f.swmr_mode = True # Unlock real-time parallel access
def instant_teleport(state_vector):
    """Captures a 'Human State' at the speed of light (RAM-limited)"""
    ts = str(time.time())
    # Pre-allocate contiguous space for zero-copy writes
    dset = f.create_dataset(f"state/{ts}", data=state_vector, chunks=None) 
    f.flush() # Instantly visible to the mobile H5 'Teleporter' page
    return ts
def time_travel_query(timestamp):
    """Rewinds the environment to a specific binary snapshot"""
    return f[f"state/{timestamp}"][:]

## 3. Maximum Speed Optimizations
To achieve "Human Teleportation" throughput (processing millions of data points per millisecond):

* Contiguous Storage: Disable chunking (chunks=None) for your state datasets. This allows the OS to memory-map the data directly, essentially "teleporting" it into your GPU or CPU without a "copy" step.
* LZF Compression: If your state data is too large for RAM, use compression='lzf'. It is the fastest compression in h5py, designed for high-speed [real-time measurements](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/11469417/is-hdf5-suitable-for-real-time-measurements).
* Pinned Memory: In the H5 mobile page, use [SharedArrayBuffer](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/SharedArrayBuffer) to share memory directly between your UI thread and the data stream for lag-free visualization.

