## The Invention: "The Fractal File-System Gallery"
Instead of a grid of files, build a zoomable, infinite canvas that treats your .h5 file like a physical "city" of data.

* The Concept: HDF5 files can store "groups within groups" indefinitely. You can build a mobile interface where users don't "click" to open folders; they pinch-to-zoom into them.
* The Technical Twist: Each "Group" in your .h5 file is rendered as a building on a 2D map. When you zoom in far enough on a building, the Python backend sends the "Sub-groups" inside it, which appear as rooms. Zoom into a room to see the "Datasets" (the actual data/images) as objects on the wall.

------------------------------
## Step 1: The "Fractal" Python Logic (fractal_engine.py)
This script creates a nested world inside your binary file.

import h5pyimport numpy as np
def build_recursive_world(file_path):
    with h5py.File(file_path, "w") as f:
        # Create a "City" group
        city = f.create_group("Neon_City")
        city.attrs["description"] = "Root of the fractal world"
        
        # Create 10 "Buildings" (Sub-groups)
        for i in range(10):
            bldg = city.create_group(f"Building_{i}")
            # Add "Rooms" inside each building
            for j in range(5):
                room = bldg.create_group(f"Room_{j}")
                # Add a "Secret" (Dataset) in each room
                data = np.random.random((10, 10))
                room.create_dataset("The_Artifact", data=data)
# Call this once to generate your world
build_recursive_world("world.h5")

## Step 2: The Mobile H5 Frontend (index.html)
Use a canvas-based library like p5.js or [PixiJS](https://pixijs.com/) within your H5 page to handle the infinite zooming.

<!-- Within your H5 page -->
<script src="https://cloudflare.com"></script>
<script>
    let zoom = 1.0;
    function draw() {
        background(0);
        scale(zoom);
        // Ask Python for the data at this specific zoom level
        if (zoom > 5.0) {
            fetch('/get-inner-layer?current_group=Neon_City')
                .then(res => res.json())
                .then(data => renderNewLayer(data));
        }
    }
    // Handle mobile pinch-to-zoom
    function mouseWheel(event) { zoom += event.delta * 0.001; }
</script>

## Why this is a unique invention:

   1. Visual Hierarchy: You are using the [HDF5 tree structure](https://www.hdfgroup.org/solutions/hdf5/) as a 3D physical space rather than a list.
   2. Efficiency: Because HDF5 only [reads data when needed](https://pythonforthelab.com/blog/how-to-use-hdf5-files-in-python/), your phone only downloads the "room" you are currently looking at, not the entire "city."
   3. Portability: The entire "world" is just one .h5 file you can share with anyone.

