To build an H5 mobile experience from scratch using Python, you should adopt a modular architecture that separates your interactive front-end from a high-performance backend capable of handling .h5 (HDF5) data.
## 1. Project Repository Structure
This structure follows modern Python [FastAPI](https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/tutorial/bigger-applications/) standards, which is better for high-performance mobile pages than older frameworks.

pyh5-mobile-app/
├── app/
│   ├── __init__.py
│   ├── main.py            # Entry point for the server
│   ├── data_handler.py    # Logic to read/write .h5 files using h5py
│   ├── static/            # H5 Mobile Front-end (HTML/CSS/JS)
│   │   ├── index.html     # Your main H5 mobile page
│   │   └── style.css      # Branding (HyperX/XESS style)
│   └── data/
│       └── store.h5       # Your actual HDF5 data file
├── requirements.txt       # Dependencies (fastapi, uvicorn, h5py)
└── README.md

## 2. Core Python Logic (data_handler.py)
Use [h5py](https://docs.h5py.org/) to manage your binary data efficiently. Unlike traditional databases, .h5 files are excellent for storing large arrays (like gaming leaderboards or user sessions).

import h5pyimport numpy as np
def save_user_score(user_id, score):
    with h5py.File('app/data/store.h5', 'a') as f:
        # Create a dataset for scores if it doesn't exist
        if 'scores' not in f:
            f.create_dataset('scores', (0,), maxshape=(None,), dtype='i')
        
        # Append new score (HDF5 is great for high-speed appending)
        dset = f['scores']
        dset.resize((len(dset) + 1,))
        dset[-1] = score

